Salah is nicknamed "The Pharaoh" by the press and his fans,<ref>{{cite news |date=17 October 2017 |title=Pharaoh Salah aims to fire up Reds too |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/sport/football/pharaoh-salah-aims-to-fire-up-reds-too |access-date=29 January 2021 |newspaper=The Straits Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Mamdouh |first=Amr |date=23 June 2017 |title=Mohamed Salah, the pharaoh who conquered Europe |url=http://en.elbalad.news/2339632 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205072838/http://en.elbalad.news/2339632 |archive-date=5 February 2018 |access-date=29 January 2021 |website=Sada El Balad}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Niyazi |first=Omar |date=26 January 2014 |title=In Pictures: The Rise of Chelsea's Pharaoh – Mohamed Salah |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2014/01/26/chelsea-pharaoh-mohamed-salah/ |access-date=29 January 2021 |website=KingFut}}</ref> while Egyptians have referred to him as the "Fourth Pyramid".<ref>{{Cite web |date=18 January 2019 |title=Mohamed Salah, The 'Fourth Pyramid of Egypt'. |url=https://scorum.com/en-us/football/@izge/mohamed-salah-the-fourth-pyramid-of-egypt |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230616185643/https://scorum.com/en-us/football/@izge/mohamed-salah-the-fourth-pyramid-of-egypt |archive-date=16 June 2023 |access-date=4 January 2025 |website=Scorum}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Mahmoud |first=Mohamed |date=22 February 2018 |title=Egypt's 'fourth pyramid' Mohamed Salah: 'He is one of us' |url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/features/egypts-fourth-pyramid-mohamed-salah-he-one-us |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230616185643/https://www.middleeasteye.net/features/egypts-fourth-pyramid-mohamed-salah-he-one-us |archive-date=16 June 2023 |access-date=4 January 2025 |work=[[Middle East Eye]]}}</ref>

The most popular chant for Salah was made by Liverpool supporters where they called him the Egyptian King – "Mo Salah, Mo Salah, Mo Salah! Running down the wing. Salah, lah, lah, lah, la-ahh, the Egyptian King!",<ref>{{citation |url=https://talksport.com/football/660139/mohamed-salah-song-what-are-the-lyrics-to-liverpool-chant/ |title=Mohamed Salah song: What are the lyrics to Liverpool fans' chant for 'The Egyptian King'? |date=6 November 2022}}</ref> to the tune of "[[Sit Down (song)|Sit Down]]" by English indie rock band [[James (band)|James]]. They also created another chant to the tune of [[Dodgy]]'s "[[Good Enough (Dodgy song)|Good Enough]]", saying that if Salah continued to score goals, they would convert to [[Islam]] – "If he's good enough for you, he's good enough for me, if he scores another few, then I'll be Muslim too."<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-43081318 |title=Mohamed Salah inspires "I'll be Muslim too" chant |website=BBC News |date=16 February 2018 |access-date=29 January 2021}}</ref> Salah has given his approval to the chant, and it has been cited as an example of inclusivity.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43208945 |title=Mohamed Salah: Is Liverpool striker's success improving engagement with Muslim fans? |last1=Din |first1=Tusdiq |date=1 March 2018 |access-date=14 March 2018 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> According to a 2021 study in the ''[[American Political Science Review]]'', Salah's transfer to Liverpool led to a 16% reduction in hate crimes in the city, as well as reducing [[Islamophobia|Islamophobic]] online rhetoric by Liverpool fans.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Alrababa’h |first1=Ala’ |last2=Marble |first2=William |last3=Mousa |first3=Salma |last4=Siegel |first4=Alexandra A. |year=2021 |title=Can Exposure to Celebrities Reduce Prejudice? The Effect of Mohamed Salah on Islamophobic Behaviors and Attitudes |journal=American Political Science Review |volume=115 |issue=4 |pages=1111–1128 |doi=10.1017/S0003055421000423 |s2cid=236279356 |issn=0003-0554|doi-access=free|hdl=20.500.11850/524343 |hdl-access=free }}</ref> Salah is devout to a degree that many other well-known Muslims sports figures are not, and his charm and apolitical persona have made him a popular figure in the UK.<ref name="AlSayyad" /> During his [[goal celebration]], Salah lays in the prostrate position to thank God in [[sujud]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/think/opinion/champions-league-final-liverpool-star-mohamed-salah-s-unapologetic-muslim-ncna877736 |title=Champions League final: Liverpool star Mohamed Salah's unapologetic Muslim faith sends extraordinary message |publisher=NBC News |date=26 May 2018 |first=Jalal |last=Baig |access-date=9 October 2018}}</ref>

Following his goal that led Egypt to the [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] finals for the first time in [[1990 FIFA World Cup|28 years]], a school in Egypt was named after him.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/1/64/351799/Egypt/Politics-/Gharbiya-governor-inaugurates-secondary-school-nam.aspx |title=Gharbiya governor inaugurates secondary school named after footballer Mohamed Salah |work=ahramonline |last=Osama |first=Sama |date=29 September 2019 |access-date=23 August 2021}}</ref> After Egypt's exit from the World Cup, Salah stayed in his home country for his pre-season holiday, and in late June, his address was accidentally leaked on Facebook. During this time, huge crowds of fans showed up at Salah's house, with Salah greeting them and signing autographs for some, although according to reports in Spain, police did arrive to cordon off his house.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/salah-comes-out-to-meet-fans-outside-of-home-after-address/1bmka2qglx9vk1ebkp65qrm7of |title=Mohamed Salah news: Liverpool star comes out to meet Egypt fans after huge crowd appears outside of home |website=Goal (website) |date=29 June 2018 |access-date=29 June 2018}}</ref>

During Liverpool's 2018 [[2018–19 Liverpool F.C. season#Pre-season|pre-season tour in the US]], American artist Brandan Odums created a mural in New York City's [[Times Square]] area displaying Salah in an Egypt kit, with the player later posting an image on social media posing next to it.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.egyptindependent.com/mohamed-salahs-mural-overlooks-times-square/ |title=NY Times Square displays Mohamed Salah's huge mural |website=Egypt Independent |first=Hend |last=El-Behary |date=10 June 2018 |access-date=8 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://twitter.com/MoSalah/status/1023581098792632320 |title=Mohamed Salah on Twitter |via=Twitter |access-date=8 September 2018}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=June 2025}} In Egypt, several murals have also been created displaying Salah's likeness, including one in the capital of Cairo.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/soccer/how-salah-became-the-main-symbol-of-hope-for-egypt-s-rising-generation-20180423-p4zb4f.html |title=How Salah became the main symbol of hope for Egypt's rising generation |newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=23 April 2018 |first1=Magdy |last1=Samaan |first2=Chris |last2=Bascombe |access-date=9 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/in-depth/features/egypt-has-now-new-pyramid-mohamed-salah-1103981319 |title=Egypt's 'fourth pyramid' Mohamed Salah: 'He is one of us' |website=Middle East Eye |date=10 January 2018 |first=Mohamed |last=Mahmoud |access-date=9 September 2018}}</ref>

A testament to his influence in the region and globally, Salah was featured on the cover of two major magazines in 2018: ''[[GQ]]'' Middle East (feature story titled "The Unstoppable Rise of Mo Salah")<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.gqmiddleeast.com/features/Mo-Salah-GQ-Middle-East-Interview-2019 |title=The Unstoppable Rise Of Mo Salah |website=Gentlemen's Quarterly |first=Ali |last=Khaled |date=16 December 2018 |access-date=21 August 2019}}</ref> and ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine's 2019 [[Time 100|''Time'' 100]] edition.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/04/17/football/mo-salah-time-magazine-100-football-liverpool-spt-intl/index.html |title=Mohamed Salah stars on cover of TIME 100 |publisher=CNN |date=17 April 2019 |access-date=21 August 2019}}</ref> An advocate of women's equality in the Middle East, Salah (in his ''Time'' 100 entry) states, "We need to change the way we treat women in our culture".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47967364 |title=Mohamed Salah named one of world's 100 most influential people by Time |date=17 April 2019 |access-date=1 June 2019 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> English comedian and Liverpool fan [[John Oliver]] wrote Salah's feature in the ''Time'' 100 issue.<ref name=":0" /> Oliver started the feature writing "Mo Salah is a better human being than he is a football player. And he's one of the best football players in the world."<ref>{{Cite magazine |title=Mohamed Salah: The 100 Most Influential People of 2019 |url=https://time.com/collection/100-most-influential-people-2019/5567841/mohamed-salah/ |first=John |last=Oliver |access-date=1 December 2020 |magazine=Time |archive-date=26 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190526034936/http://time.com/collection/100-most-influential-people-2019/5567841/mohamed-salah/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> Despite being named as the "GQ Middle East Man of the Year" in 2019, another GQ photoshoot, with Brazilian model [[Alessandra Ambrosio]], caused him some criticism in the Islamic world.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://en.as.com/en/2019/10/22/football/1571761044_447975.html |title=Mohamed Salah's GQ photoshoot causes outrage in Egypt |newspaper=AS |first=Alex |last=del Río |date=22 October 2019 |access-date=29 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200716202853/https://en.as.com/en/2019/10/22/football/1571761044_447975.html |archive-date=16 July 2020}}</ref> In January 2020, it was announced that Salah would be honoured with a wax statue at [[Madame Tussauds]] in London.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://egyptianstreets.com/2020/01/25/mo-salah-first-egyptian-honoured-with-wax-statue-at-madame-tussauds-in-london/ |title=Mo Salah Honoured with Wax Statue at Madame Tussauds in London |date=25 January 2020|access-date=25 January 2020 |website=Egyptian Streets}}</ref>

